\section{Post Processing Methods}

\begin{frame}[squeeze]
\frametitle{Post Processing/Filtering}

\noindent	Instead of addressing the Nyquist limit, some methods try to smooth aliasing artifacts from the image

\only<1>	{
	\begin{itemize}
		\item	Morphological Filtering (MLAA)\supercite{MLAAIntel} among the oldest
		\begin{itemize}
			\item	attempts to determine original geometry and blend appropriately
		\end{itemize}
		
		\item	Temporal Filtering (TAA) utilizes \textbf{reprojection} and is also an older method
		\begin{itemize}
			\item	\textbf{reprojection}\supercite{Reprojection} involves reusing already calculated results, allowing for improved performance
			\item	\textbf{Amortized Super-Sampling}\supercite{TAA} uses sub-pixel jittererd samples to potentially recreate 2x2 SSAA
		\end{itemize}
		
		% \item	Fast Approximate (FXAA)\supercite{FXAA} trades accuracy for speed
		\item	Fast Approximate (FXAA)\supercite{FXAA} focuses on speed over accuracy
		\begin{itemize}
			\item	finds edges, applies a perpendicular sub-pixel shift, and resamples
			\item	does have an early exit to protect some edges, and quality levels
			\item	has low-pass filter to remove/reduce high frequency details
		\end{itemize}	
	\end{itemize}
}

\only<2>{
	\begin{itemize}
		\item	Enhanced Sub-Pixel Morphological Filtering (SMAA)\supercite{JIMENEZ2012_CGF} improves upon MLAA
		\begin{itemize}
			\item	Improved morphological filtering engine
			\begin{itemize}
				\item	pre-computed blending textures
				\item	supports arbitrary sample positions
				\item	diagonal pattern detection
			\end{itemize}
			
			\item	Modular design
			\begin{itemize}
				\item	SMAA ~1x - morphological engine only
				\item	SMAA T2x - SMAA 1x with two temporal super-samples
				\item	SMAA S2x - SMAA 1x with two spatial multi-samples
				\item	SMAA ~4x - SMAA 1x + SMAA T2x + SMAA S2x
			\end{itemize}
		\end{itemize}
	\end{itemize}
}
\end{frame}

